observations.recommendation:
We recommended that Management:
a. Immediately order the conduct of the one-time cleansing of PPE accounts under COA Circular No. 2020-006, to avoid the continued and further misstatement of these accounts in the ensuing years;
b. Require the Inventory Committee to:
b.1 Regularly conduct a complete annual physical count of Property, Plant, and Equipment (PPE); and
b.2 Ensure that the information contained in the Report on Physical Count of Property, Plant and Equipment (RPCPPE) is complete and based on the actual physical count;
c. Direct the Municipal Accountant to:
c.1 Maintain property ledger cards to reflect the sufficient and particular description of each PPE item;
c.2 Ensure that the road lot component of the local road network is properly accounted for and included in the financial reports;
c.3 Maintain the appropriate ledger cards for road networks following the format in Annex D of COA Circular No. 2015-008 dated November 23, 2015;
c.4 Observe the proper disclosure of the road network systems in the Notes to the Financial Statements in accordance with Annex B of the above-mentioned Circular; and
c.5 Immediately record in the GF books the acquired dump truck, including the adjustment for unrecognized depreciation for CY 2023;
d. Direct the General Services Officer (GSO) to:
d.1 Maintain an updated Local Road Inventory and Road Map;
d.2 Prepare the Report on Local Road Network as provided in Annex A of the above-mentioned Circular; and
d.3 Maintain a complete and updated property card for each item of PPE of the LGU based on per PPE item physical count;
e. Require the Municipal Accountant and GSO of the periodic reconciliation of property records; and the persons/departments concerned to conduct one-time cleansing of PPE in accordance with COA Circular 2020-006; and
f. Direct the Municipal Engineer to complete the inspection of the road network assets and furnish the Municipal Accountant and GSO with the complete description and cost segregation of all road projects.

We recommended that Management:
a. Require all end-users to meticulously and judiciously plan all their procurement activities by specifically identifying the schedule for each procurement activity and the contract implementation in their respective Procurement Management Plans (PPMPs);
b. Direct the Bids and Awards Committee (BAC) to:
b.1 Instruct the BAC Secretariat to consolidate all the PPMPs from the end-users, after evaluation by the Budget Officer, into a single Annual Procurement Plan (APP);
b.1.2 Accurately prepare the APP and effect any revisions thereof, as necessary;
b.1.3 Reflect all the procurement activities specified in the approved APP in the Procurement Monitoring Report (PMR);
b.1.4 Strictly monitor the major procurement activities conducted and regularly update the PMR of its dates; and
b.1.5 Observe complete and timely submission of APP and PMR to the Government Procurement Policy Board (GPPB), copy furnish the Auditor;
b.2 Ensure that all procurements conducted are in accordance with the approved APP; and
b.3 Strictly observe the procurement timelines prescribed in the RIRR of RA No. 9184 including its Annex C.

We recommended that Management require the Bids and Awards Committee (BAC) to:
a. Complete the procurement activities within the earliest possible time or at least not beyond the maximum allowed period;
b. Send invitations to observers in the conduct of negotiated procurement under Section 53.1 (Two-Failed Biddings) of the RIRR of RA No. 9184;
c. Prepare a resolution recommending the award of contract for procurements under alternative mode to serve as the reckoning date of 15 calendar days (CDs) within which the Head of Procuring Entity (HoPE) shall disapprove, or approve and issue a Notice of Award (NOA) to the supplier;
d. Observe the required posting of Notice of Award (NOA), Contract/Purchase Order (PO), including the Notice to Proceed (NTP) if necessary, amounting over Php 50,000.00 to comply with the policy of transparency of government; and
e. Review the guidelines that shall be followed in the conduct of alternative modes of procurement and strictly apply the same.

We recommended that Management:
a. Require the responsible LGU and barangay officials to report on the status of the utilization of the distributed sand and gravel, without prejudice to imposition of appropriate sanctions for any loss or wastage thereof;
b. Direct the Municipal Planning and Development Officer (MPDO) to strictly monitor the implementation of projects charged against the 20 percent Development Fund to ensure that the intended socio-economic development and environmental management outcomes are achieved;
c. Direct the Municipal Engineer to:
c.1 Inspect and monitor all infrastructure projects, both those fully and partially funded by the LGU, to ensure that the utilization of construction funds is in accordance with the existing laws and rules;
c.2 Conduct detailed engineering studies and prepare a complete program of work (POW) based on the specific requirements of the project and construction site; and
c.3 Refrain from providing piecemeal POW based on funding sources to enable proper assessment of the usability of the project;
d. Require the BAC and its Technical Working Group (TWG) to provide justification or explanation on the noted deficiency in the conduct of post-qualification of the bidder, without prejudice to holding them responsible for non-compliance with the provisions of RA No. 9184; and
e. Instruct the GSO and other employees concerned to promptly accomplish and submit to the Municipal Accountant the necessary documents for the timely recording of transactions.

We recommended that Management require the Municipal Engineer’s Office (MEO), in coordination with the Municipal Planning and Development Office (MPDO) to:
a. Regularly monitor the implementation of all planned PPAs of the LGU;
b. Timely update the Report on Government Programs, Projects, and Activities (GPPAs) regarding the status of implementation;
c. Ensure that appropriate project signboards which are compliant with the prescribed format and with complete details concerning the PPAs are placed within the project site for public information and validation; and
d. Notify the Audit Team within ten days after the award of the infrastructure project or before the start of the program/activity that the appropriate project signboards and/or public notices are already posted for validation.

We recommended that Management:
a. direct the Inventory Committee to conduct the physical inventory taking of supplies and materials once every semester and prepare and submit the corresponding RPCI to the Audit Team within the set timeline;
b. require the GSO to submit to the Municipal Accountant the required RIS as basis in the issuance of supplies and the SSMI for the recording of the issued/distributed supplies;
c. require the GSO and the Municipal Accountant to maintain Stock Cards and Properly Ledger Cards for each type of Inventory;
d. direct the Municipal Accountant to prepare the adjusting entries to correct the corresponding asset and liability accounts amounting to ₱3.59 million if the subject Inventory accounts were not yet delivered; and
e. refrain from premature recording of asset and liability in the absence of proof of receipt of goods.

We recommended that Management require the Municipal Accountant to:
a. prepare the adjusting entries in the General Fund books to record to the appropriate PPE account the completed projects amounting to ₱13.10 million, procured equipment amounting to ₱72,900;
b. issue Property Acknowledgement Receipt (PAR) to the employee of Sipocot- BFP who received the motorcycle and television set to establish accountability to the issued assets;
c. prepare the adjusting entry in the Trust Fund book to record the on-going project amounting to ₱445,000 to the appropriate CIP account during construction period as provided under Section 104 of NGAS Manual for LGUs; and
d. prepare the adjusting entries on the unrecorded depreciation expense on completed projects.

We recommended that Management:
a. allocate budget for the ₱25.93 million accrued payable for the terminal leave benefits earned by its employees;
b. include in the Annual Budget every year the appropriation for the accrued payable on terminal leave benefits earned by each employee per year to ensure that employee benefits are properly accounted for;
c. set-up a special fund for the accrued earned leave of employees to defray expenses of employees’ benefits in the future; and
d. direct the Municipal Accountant to make the necessary adjusting entries to record the accrued liability pertaining to the earned leave benefits of the employees after ensuring the correctness of the accumulated leave credit balances of employees as of December 31, 2020.

We recommended that Management:
a. stop the practice of making advance payment for gasoline;
b. direct the Municipal Accountant to record only goods already delivered as provided under Section 141 of MNGAs for LGUs;
c. direct the Municipal Accountant to reconcile the LGUs books with the record of the supplier;
d. ensure that before any vehicle leave the compound of the LGU, the concerned driver of the vehicle has secured first an approved driver’s trip ticket from the designated approving officer; and
e. consider establishing either a Petty Cash Fund (PCF) for gasoline or negotiating on account or charge purchases of gasoline from suppliers, payable on terms agreeable to both parties.

We recommended that Management:
a. direct the BAC Secretariat to properly evaluate, review and consolidate the PPMPs of various offices into a comprehensive, workable and realistic Annual Procurement Plan (APP) which would reflect the details of the procurement activities that it seeks to undertake within the calendar year;
b. strictly follow the procurement methods and activities as stated in their Annual Procurement Plan;
c. whenever practicable, consider consolidation of purchase requests for supplies needed by the different offices and adopt bulk purchases to promote efficiency in the procurement process; and
d. stop the procurement of supplies on a reimbursement bases, unless the circumstances warrant its application.

We recommended that Management:
1) create an Inventory Committee which will conduct the actual count of all supplies and materials on stock;
2) submit to the Audit Team the properly accomplished RPCI not later than July 31 and January 31 of each year for the first and second semesters, respectively;
3) reconcile the Inventory Accounts per books with the actual supplies at hand; and
4) appoint a General Services Officer to take charge in the provision of supplies and procurement of services as well as to deliver basic services upon provisions of adequate facilities and to conduct physical count of Inventory and Property, Plant and Equipment.

We recommended that Management:

provide an appropriate alternative on proper waste disposal while still in the process of waiting approval of the 10-year Solid Waste Management Plan/Program by the DENR;

provide sufficient appropriation for the implementation of the alternative program;

require the Municipal Management Board to strategically plan to ensure implementation and enforcement of the provisions of the Act; and

require the MENRO in coordination with the Municipal Management Board to the respond to the matter and ensure that the 10-year Solid Waste Management Plan/Program for the safe and sanitary management of the solid waste generation is consistent with the national framework and in accordance with the Act and of the policies set by the National Solid Waste Management Commission

We recommended and Management agreed to:
create an Inventory Committee which will conduct the actual count of all supplies and materials on stock;
submit to the Audit Team the properly accomplished RPCI not later than July 31 and January 31 of each year for the first and second semesters, respectively;
reconcile the Inventory Accounts per books with the actual supplies at hand; and
appoint a General Services Officer to take charge in the provision of supplies and procurement of services as well as to deliver basic services upon provisions of adequate facilities and to conduct physical count of Inventory and Property, Plant and Equipment.

We recommended that Management direct the:
Disposal Committee particularly its Secretary to gather and submit the supporting documents to the Municipal Accountant for correcting the entry made for said transaction;
Municipal Accountant’s Office to make the necessary correcting entry for the transaction pertaining to the sale of property and equipment owned by the municipality; and strict adherence to the pertinent provisions of COA Circular No. 2015-009 and COA Circular No. 89-296 as to divestment or disposal of assets, otherwise transactions shall be disallowed in audit.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor, in order to facilitate preparation and consolidation of APP, initiate a workshop wherein all the Heads of each end-user unit of the Municipality shall prepare their respective Project Procurement Management Plan (PPMP) for their different programs, activities, and projects (PAPs). The PPMP output shall then be submitted to the Budget Officer for her evaluation whether it is within the approved budget of the corresponding end-user unit.
We also recommended that the Municipal Mayor require from the Head of the BAC Secretariar the preparation of the Consolidated APP as prescribed in Section 7 of the Revised Implementing Rules and Regulations of R.A. 9184 during the year-and in the ensuing years:

DILG-DBM Joint Memorandum Circular 2011-1;

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor:
1 in the preparation of its budget for the 20% Local Development Fund in the ensuing year, specifically describe and state the projects and programs to be implemented to the barangays to dispense the issuance of SB authorization to the LCE;
require the Municipal Accountant to secure liquidation report of the fund transferred from the 36 recipient barangays and to strictly comply with the provisions of COA Circular No. 2012-001 prior the release of financial assistance to barangays in the succeeding years:
